<DOC><DOCNO> AP880302-0275 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-88 0139EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   03-02 0539</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0560</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   American Standard Inc., target of a hostile$2.12 billion takeover attempt by Black andamp; Decker Corp., says it istaking steps to sweeten the cash portion of a recapitalizationdesigned to foil the bid.   The company said Tuesday it had begun talks with unidentifiedthird parties regarding the possible sale of debt securities as ameans of increasing the cash part of the recapitalization. Theproposal would pay shareholders $1.9 billion and give them a stakein the recapitalized company.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Three companies have introduced new high-poweredcomputers ranging from a ``personal supercomputer'' to amini-supercomputer designed to take on industry leaders.   Apollo Computer Inc. said Tuesday it was producing a workstationfor scientists and engineers with supercomputer power thatoutperforms anything in its price range: $69,900 to $130,000.   Ardent Computer Corp., a Sunnyvale, Calif.-based start-up,announced its first product, a graphics supercomputer in about thesame price and performance range as Apollo's.   Convex Computer Corp. of Richardson, Texas, aiming at a moreexpensive portion of the market, unveiled a more powerful new lineof mini-supercomputers it hopes will cut into Cray Research Inc.'sdomination of that market.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Inland Steel Co. says it may permanently closefour mills and idle at least 750 workers in a move the UnitedSteelworkers of America said was designed to coerce workerconcessions.   The company told USW Local 1010 Tuesday that it planned to closefour shaped-products mills at its Indiana Harbor Works in EastChicago, Ind., in 90 days. But Inland also indicated it was willingto ``discuss the proposal or to receive any alternatives to theproposed course of action.''</TEXT><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Senior officials from Britain, France, West Germanyand Spain have ordered Europe's Airbus Industrie to try to reach anagreement on industrial and commercial cooperation with McDonnellDouglas Corp. by mid-1988.   The decision emerged Tuesday at the end of a one-day meeting oftransport ministers and chief executives of the industrial partnersin the European commercial aircraft group.   Aviation industry observers said it was the latest display ofEurope's eagerness to penetrate the lucrative U.S. market whiletrying to reduce trade friction over American claims of unfaircompetition by Airbus.</TEXT><DATELINE>FREEHOLD, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal authorities have arrested a majorWall Street stock trader after a state judge ordered the manreleased on his own recognizance on charges he plotted to shootfinancier Ivan Boesky.   Superior Court Judge Alvin Y. Milberg agreed to release John A.Mulheren Jr. on Tuesday but did not consent to conditions thatwould allow the millionaire trader to be transferred to a hospitalfor treatment of manic depression.   Mulheren remained in the Monmouth County Jail during the hearingand was arrested immediately afterward by four U.S. marshals onseparate charges, authorities said.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The stock market slipped off its post-crash peakTuesday as the Dow Jones industrial average fell 1.16 points to2,070.46.   The dollar fell marginally against most key currencies.   Bond prices were little changed in light dealings.   Wheat futures prices fell, other grains and soybeans endedmostly lower, energy futures retreated and most livestock and meatfutures advanced.</TEXT></DOC>